Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Tuesday! Not just any Tuesday - Happy Election Day!=C2=A0
The fun challenge with sending a newsletter that goes out every Tuesday is =
what do you write on a day when you know no one will read it? I=E2=80=99m c=
ertainly not going to send a Deep Dive on Election Day. I=E2=80=99m not goi=
ng to send something that takes weeks of research, or something that contai=
ns my very best ideas. I could wait a day and send on Wednesday, which I oc=
casionally do, but tomorrow might be even worse! Polymarket has a market li=
ve for when the AP will call the election, and Wednesday is in the lead wit=
h 46% [ https://substack.com/redirect/b661e903-b174-4015-aabd-b9db38004eec?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I cou=
ld write something that reminds you, once again, that no matter what happen=
s today or who AP calls the winner tomorrow, we=E2=80=99ll be fine, great e=
ven, but I=E2=80=99ve told you that before [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
92d3faaa-5d3c-4797-9357-00dfda172429?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and you either buy it or you don=E2=80=99t.=
=C2=A0
No, none of those work. So instead, I=E2=80=99ll make a short PSA of the so=
rt that I normally wouldn=E2=80=99t find the occasion to send: you should r=
ead more books.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=C2=A0
Read More Books
You will probably spend a lot of time on the internet today.=C2=A0
You will doomscroll and watch polls. That=E2=80=99s fine. I will too. You m=
ay tweet things that Next Week You won=E2=80=99t be proud of, and that Next=
 Decade You might not even recognize as you. Try not to.=C2=A0
But while you=E2=80=99re here, on the internet, might I suggest that you sp=
end some of your time here on amazon.com, buying books.=C2=A0
When the haze clears, instead of a sore thumb and a tarnished reputation, y=
ou will be left with a pile (physical or metaphorical) of books to read.=C2=
=A0
Next Week You will be proud of you. Next Decade You will thank you.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CBut I don=E2=80=99t have time to read,=E2=80=9D you say. =E2=80=9C=
I am simply too busy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s not true.=C2=A0
The average American spends 16 minutes per day reading. Only 46% of America=
ns read a book in the past year, and only 18% have read ten or more. Meanwh=
ile, we spend nearly three hours watching TV and two hours and fourteen min=
utes on social media (often while watching TV). Some of that time might be =
better spent reading (I am reminding myself of this as much as you).=C2=A0
But what if you=E2=80=99re one of those rare few who already doesn=E2=80=99=
t watch TV, doesn=E2=80=99t waste time on social media? What if you really =
are too busy?=C2=A0
Warren Buffett is currently sitting on $325 billion in cash that he needs t=
o figure out how to deploy. Surely he is too busy to read.=C2=A0
He is not. Warren Buffett spends 80% of his working day reading and thinkin=
g [ https://substack.com/redirect/5a963c76-396a-4532-aee0-6eb33f639e3b?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
An interviewer asked [ https://substack.com/redirect/8ca411e7-075d-4be5-a27=
8-656c18631b9c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] Buffett, =E2=80=9CHow do you keep up with all the media and inform=
ation that goes on in our crazy world and in your world of Berkshire Hathaw=
ay? What=E2=80=99s your media routine?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Buffett replied, =E2=80=9CI read and read and read. I probably read five to=
 six hours a day.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Maybe Buffett is an unfair comparison. His job is to wait for fat pitches, =
to swing only occasionally when, like Babe Ruth, he knows he=E2=80=99s goin=
g to hit a home run. His is a job that allows for, demands, quiet contempla=
tion.=C2=A0
Barack Obama had a very different job, one full of meetings and travel and =
world-changing decisions. While President, Barack Obama read at least 30 mi=
nutes every night. He even read fiction, said it helped him better imagine =
and understand the lives of other people during his presidency.=C2=A0
There is no good excuse, only choices.=C2=A0
But why choose to read?=C2=A0
In 2020, Byrne Hobart [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb9d471e-f39d-4c03-aa=
ec-c595fd81ed6f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], who reads an intimidating amount, wrote an essay titled =E2=80=
=9CRead [ https://substack.com/redirect/276b7025-fb89-4101-a959-b350b7cd3ed=
a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=E2=
=80=9D in which he, too, argued that you should read more if you want to le=
arn:=C2=A0
The way serious people learn is by reading. The way they share important in=
formation is by writing it down. Read, read, read. Rich people read a lot =
=E2=80=94 Forbes asked [ https://substack.com/redirect/614ed062-a543-4532-b=
7c0-044df0494450?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] a while ago, and the modal answer was two hours per day. (The na=
tional average is about twenty minutes [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca1e=
9631-d5d7-4e54-9b6d-ef5c01bf361e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].) One respondent claimed eight plus.
The science backs Byrne up: reading improves your ability to focus, slows m=
emory deterioration and enhances memory, boosts verbal skills, and improves=
 your ability to connect different pieces of information and ideas.=C2=A0
I want to linger on this last point for a second, because to me, it=E2=80=
=99s one of the most fun parts about reading. It=E2=80=99s a reward that ta=
kes a little time to earn, but begins to pay off with increasing frequency =
the more you read.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ll give a direct example.=C2=A0
Right now, I=E2=80=99m reading The Fish That Ate the Whale: The Life and Ti=
mes of America=E2=80=99s Banana King [ https://substack.com/redirect/0b1897=
fd-150d-4f9b-9392-a8a7cd5d4578?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a truly wonderful book on the life of Sam Zemurra=
y by Rich Cohen. On page 184, Cohen writes about the small socialism proble=
m Zemurray faced in Guatemala during the time of Jacobo Arbenz and Che Guev=
era, and how the Banana King planned to deal with it.=C2=A0
Among the most effective of Zemurray=E2=80=99s government men was Tommy Cor=
coran, known in the White House and Congress and every tavern in D.C. as To=
mmy the Cork: you push him down here, he pops up over there=E2=80=A6 Corcor=
an briefed Zemurray on the thinking of top government officials. For exampl=
e, under what conditions would President Truman be willing to go to war on =
the isthmus?=C2=A0
Tommy the Cork isn=E2=80=99t a name you forget, particularly when you last =
read it so recently.=C2=A0
Last week, I read Means of Ascent [ https://substack.com/redirect/57011680-=
0719-43fd-85a7-58f438be0aa7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Book Two of Robert Caro=E2=80=99s The Years of Lyndo=
n Johnson series. On page 10, Caro describes how FDR had decided to help th=
e young Texan politician after their first meeting in 1937:=C2=A0
It had been Corcoran whom the President had telephoned, upon his return fro=
m Texas, to say, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve just met the most remarkable young m=
an=E2=80=9D and to issue an order: =E2=80=9Chelp him with anything you can.=
=E2=80=9D
The same person =E2=80=93 a person I=E2=80=99d never heard of until last we=
ek =E2=80=93 was deputized by FDR to help LBJ and, a decade later, by the B=
anana King to combat Che!=C2=A0
That is a very specific connection and one that, apart from writing it here=
, I don=E2=80=99t know that I=E2=80=99ll ever have the occasion to employ. =
But stumbling upon the Cork for a second time was better than a dopamine hi=
t; it felt like snapping in a puzzle piece that revealed the full picture.=
=C2=A0
Which brings me to a final point: how should you read? Or, what should you =
read?=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve always read a lot, and I=E2=80=99ve always been frustrated by =
how little of what I read I retain. I was talking to someone about this a c=
ouple weeks ago, someone who reads and remembers much more than I do, and I=
 suggested that my memory is just hopelessly bad, naturally worse than his.
He disagreed with my conclusion : =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s possible you read t=
oo much nonsense. I don=E2=80=99t tend to.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I thought about that a lot, and I think he=E2=80=99s right. Or, at least, t=
he comment changed the way I think about what and how to read.=C2=A0
Here, I can bring it back to tech for a second, because this is a newslette=
r about tech after all, even on election day.=C2=A0
Benchmark partner Sarah Tavel has this idea about building a =E2=80=9Cwhite=
 hot core [ https://substack.com/redirect/4c712c95-ea8d-4bf0-b2f1-a8d37aa29=
0ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=
=80=9D when starting a marketplace. The idea is that you shouldn=E2=80=99t =
try to serve everyone at once, at the beginning, but should begin by nailin=
g the product for a very specific, constrained problem or niche. Prioritize=
 retention over growth. Then, and only then, once your small niche of users=
 really loves your product, you can expand outward into adjacent niches and=
 problems.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve always been a little jealous of the way that it seems people l=
ike Byrne and Ben Thompson=E2=80=99s brains work. From the outside, it seem=
s like they have a scaffolding in their brain, and then, whenever any new i=
nformation comes in, they can simply hang it on that scaffolding. That=E2=
=80=99s why they can write five excellent essays a week when I struggle to =
write one.=C2=A0
I haven=E2=80=99t asked them about this, but what I think is actually happe=
ning =E2=80=93 other than just raw horsepower =E2=80=93 is something simila=
r to Sarah=E2=80=99s white hot core idea.=C2=A0
Read a lot of high-quality stuff on a certain topic or time period. Recogni=
ze connections, reinforce them, prioritize retention over growth. Then, and=
 only then, once your core is established, expand outward.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s like constructing a map instead of dotting a bunch of dots.=C2=
=A0
In The Best Essay [ https://substack.com/redirect/9e080896-b770-4da5-9d66-2=
25db4fb6f37?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], Paul Graham writes:
An essay should ordinarily start with what I'm going to call a question, th=
ough I mean this in a very general sense: it doesn't have to be a question =
grammatically, just something that acts like one in the sense that it spurs=
 some response.
I would argue that the same is true for reading.=C2=A0
The best reading should ordinarily start with what I=E2=80=99m going to cal=
l a question, though I mean that in a very general sense.
My current question =E2=80=93 though it=E2=80=99s more of an obsession than=
 a question =E2=80=93 is trying to learn more about Vertical Integrators [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/60e6b839-815f-432b-9398-4b1338158728?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] than anyone in=
 the world.=C2=A0
Over the past couple of months, I=E2=80=99ve read American Colossus, The Pr=
ize, Saudi Inc., Zero to One, Cable Cowboy, Kochland, My Life and Work, Emp=
ires of Light, The Wright Brothers, Dealers of Lightning, The First Tycoon,=
 and The Fish That Ate the Whale. I have about ten more books on the topic =
loaded on the Kindle and ready to go. The other day, I read a 1990 economic=
s paper that, just last year, might have seemed too dry to finish, but now,=
 read like a Rosetta Stone.=C2=A0
If you asked me a question about facts and figures and people and theories,=
 the kinds of questions my weak memory never would have been able to handle=
 before, I can actually answer them!=C2=A0
And when I read an off-topic book, like Means of Ascent, that takes place i=
n a similar time period, I can see connections there, too. The obvious ones=
, like =E2=80=9CTommy the Cork shows up in both,=E2=80=9D and less obvious =
ones, like the fact that both LBJ and Zemurray justified any means in the p=
ursuit of their ends.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s one theme that pops up over and over again, one that might =
be relevant on a day like today, when half the country will inevitably thin=
k that the world is ending, that forces of evil beyond their control have d=
oomed the country and their own lives to chaos and decline: agency.=C2=A0
The greatness of Zemurray lies in the fact that he never lost faith in his =
ability to salvage a situation. Bad things happened to him as bad things ha=
ppen to everyone, but unlike so many he was never tempted by failure. He ne=
ver felt powerless or trapped. He was, as I said, an optimist. He stood in =
constant defiance.
There are similar passages in the books on LBJ, Vanderbilt, Ford, the Wrigh=
t Brothers, the Koch Brothers, Westinghouse, Edison, and Malone. Reading ab=
out all of these people in rapid succession =E2=80=93 people who lived and =
built in a time when the world was a much harsher place than ours is today =
=E2=80=93 provides a reminder that whatever happens outside of you, you can=
 choose to give up or you can look at the board as it is and figure out how=
 to play your next move.=C2=A0
Maybe as importantly as the specifics, reading gives you an understanding t=
hat everything that you think is novel and terrifying has happened before, =
and that people have survived.=C2=A0
So I=E2=80=99ll leave you with a passage from CS Lewis that Michael Dempsey=
 tweeted this morning [ https://substack.com/redirect/3c1d5090-e182-43ac-b6=
33-ae55ff30bb54?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIf we are all going to be destroyed by an atomic bomb, let that bo=
mb when it comes find us doing sensible and human things =E2=80=93 praying,=
 working, teaching, reading, listening to music, bathing the children, play=
ing tennis, chatting to our friends over a pint and a game of darts =E2=80=
=93 not huddled together like frightened sheep and thinking about bombs. Th=
ey may break our bodies (any microbe can do that) but they need not dominat=
e our minds.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
So go vote, enjoy today for what it is, spend time with family and friends,=
 and read.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIn other words, do not let us begin by exaggerating the novelty of=
 our situation.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox Friday wi=
th a Weekly Dose.=20
God Bless America =F0=9F=87=BA=F0=9F=87=B8
Thanks for reading,
Packy

