 understand the lives of other people during his presidency.&#160;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;">There is no good excuse, only choices.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;">But why choose to read?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In 2020, </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/cb9d471e-f39d-4c03-aaec-c595fd81=
ed6f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" re=
l style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Byrne Hobar=
t</a><span>, who reads an intimidating amount, wrote an essay titled &#8220=
;</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/276b7025-fb89-4101-a959-b3=
50b7cd3eda?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Read<=
/a><span>,&#8221; in which he, too, argued that you should read more if you=
 want to learn:&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid=
 #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"=
><em><span>The way serious people learn is by reading. The way they share i=
mportant information is by writing it down. Read, read, read. Rich people r=
ead a lot &#8212; Forbes </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/61=
4ed062-a543-4532-b7c0-044df0494450?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decor=
ation: underline;">asked</a><span> a while ago, and the modal answer was tw=
o hours per day. (The national average is about </span><a href=3D"https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/ca1e9631-d5d7-4e54-9b6d-ef5c01bf361e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">twenty minutes</a><span>.) One re=
spondent claimed eight plus.</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
The science backs Byrne up: reading improves your ability to focus, slows m=
emory deterioration and enhances memory, boosts verbal skills, and improves=
 your ability to connect different pieces of information and ideas.&#160;</=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">I want to linger on this last point for a second, becau=
se to me, it&#8217;s one of the most fun parts about reading. It&#8217;s a =
reward that takes a little time to earn, but begins to pay off with increas=
ing frequency the more you read.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I&#8217;ll give=
 a direct example.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Right now, I&#8217;m re=
ading </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/0b1897fd-150d-4f9=
b-9392-a8a7cd5d4578?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underlin=
e;">The Fish That Ate the Whale: The Life and Times of America&#8217;s Bana=
na King</a></em><span>, a truly wonderful book on the life of Sam Zemurray =
by Rich Cohen. On page 184, Cohen writes about the small socialism problem =
Zemurray faced in Guatemala during the time of Jacobo Arbenz and Che Guever=
a, and how the Banana King planned to deal with it.&#160;</span></p><blockq=
uote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;">=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Among the most effective of =
Zemurray&#8217;s government men was </span><strong>Tommy Corcoran</strong><=
span>, known in the White House and Congress and every tavern in D.C. as To=
mmy the Cork: you push him down here, he pops up over there&#8230; Corcoran=
 briefed Zemurray on the thinking of top government officials. For example,=
 under what conditions would President Truman be willing to go to war on th=
e isthmus?&#160;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Tommy the Co=
rk isn&#8217;t a name you forget, particularly when you last read it so rec=
ently.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Last week, I read </span><em><a hre=
f=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/57011680-0719-43fd-85a7-58f438be0aa7?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Means of Ascent</=
a></em><span>, Book Two of Robert Caro&#8217;s </span><em>The Years of Lynd=
on Johnson</em><span> series. On page 10, Caro describes how FDR had decide=
d to help the young Texan politician after their first meeting in 1937:&#16=
0;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 2=
0px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>It had b=
een </span><strong>Corcoran</strong><span> whom the President had telephone=
d, upon his return from Texas, to say, &#8220;I&#8217;ve just met the most =
remarkable young man&#8221; and to issue an order: &#8220;help him with any=
thing you can.&#8221;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The sam=
e person &#8211; a person I&#8217;d never heard of until last week &#8211; =
was deputized by FDR to help LBJ and, a decade later, by the Banana King to=
 combat Che!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That is a very specific connection =
and one that, apart from writing it here, I don&#8217;t know that I&#8217;l=
l ever have the occasion to employ. But stumbling upon the Cork for a secon=
d time was better than a dopamine hit; it felt like snapping in a puzzle pi=
ece that revealed the full picture.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Which brings=
 me to a final point: how should you read? Or, what should you read?&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I&#8217;ve always read a lot, and I&#8217;ve always be=
en frustrated by how little of what I read I retain. I was talking to someo=
ne about this a couple weeks ago, someone who reads and remembers much more=
 than I do, and I suggested that my memory is just hopelessly bad, naturall=
y worse than his.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>He disagreed with my conclusio=
n : &#8220;</span><strong>It&#8217;s possible you read too much nonsense. I=
 don&#8217;t tend to.</strong><span>&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">I thought about that a lot, and I think he&#8217;s right. Or, at least, =
the comment changed the way I think about what and how to read.&#160;</p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">Here, I can bring it back to tech for a second, because thi=
s is a newsletter about tech after all, even on election day.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Benchmark partner Sarah Tavel has this idea about build=
ing a &#8220;</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4c712c95-ea8d-=
4bf0-b2f1-a8d37aa290ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: under=
line;">white hot core</a><span>&#8221; when starting a marketplace. The ide=
a is that you shouldn&#8217;t try to serve everyone at once, at the beginni=
ng, but should begin by nailing the product for a very specific, constraine=
d problem or niche. Prioritize retention over growth. Then, and only then, =
once your small niche of users really loves your product, you can expand ou=
tward into adjacent niches and problems.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
I&#8217;ve always been a little jealous of the way that it seems people lik=
e Byrne and Ben Thompson&#8217;s brains work. From the outside, it seems li=
ke they have a scaffolding in their brain, and then, whenever any new infor=
mation comes in, they can simply hang it on that scaffolding. That&#8217;s =
why they can write five excellent essays a week when I struggle to write on=
e.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I haven&#8217;t asked them about this, but wh=
at I think is actually happening &#8211; other than just raw horsepower &#8=
211; is something similar to Sarah&#8217;s white hot core idea.&#160;</p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">Read a lot of high-quality stuff on a certain topic or time=
 period. Recognize connections, reinforce them, prioritize retention over g=
rowth. Then, and only then, once your core is established, expand outward.&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It&#8217;s like constructing a map instead of do=
tting a bunch of dots.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In </span><em><a hr=
ef=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9e080896-b770-4da5-9d66-225db4fb6f37?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">The Best Essay</a=
><span>, </span></em><span>Paul Graham writes:</span></p><blockquote style=
=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>An essay should ordinarily start with what=
 I'm going to call a question, though I mean this in a very general sense: =
it doesn't have to be a question grammatically, just something that acts li=
ke one in the sense that it spurs some response.</em></p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;">I would argue that the same is true for reading.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">The best reading should ordinarily start with what I&#8217;m =
going to call a question, though I mean that in a very general sense.</p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>My current question &#8211; though it&#8217;s more of=
 an obsession than a question &#8211; is trying to learn more about </span>=
<a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/60e6b839-815f-432b-9398-4b13381587=
28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Vertical Inte=
grators</a><span> than anyone in the world.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>Over the past couple of months, I&#8217;ve read </span><em>America=
n Colossus, The Prize, Saudi Inc., Zero to One, Cable Cowboy, Kochland, My =
Life and Work, Empires of Light, The Wright Brothers, Dealers of Lightning,=
 The First Tycoon, </em><span>and </span><em>The Fish That Ate the Whale. <=
/em><span>I have about ten more books on the topic loaded on the Kindle and=
 ready to go. The other day, I read a 1990 economics paper that, just last =
year, might have seemed too dry to finish, but now, read like a Rosetta Sto=
ne.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you asked me a question about fact=
s and figures and people and theories, the kinds of questions my weak memor=
y never would have been able to handle before, I can actually answer them!&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>And when I read an off-topic book, like </=
span><em>Means of Ascent</em><span>, that takes place in a similar time per=
iod, I can see connections there, too. The obvious ones, like &#8220;Tommy =
the Cork shows up in both,&#8221; and less obvious ones, like the fact that=
 both LBJ and Zemurray justified any means in the pursuit of their ends.&#1=
60;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>There&#8217;s one theme that pops up =
over and over again, one that might be relevant on a day like today, when h=
alf the country will inevitably think that the world is ending, that forces=
 of evil beyond their control have doomed the country and their own lives t=
o chaos and decline: </span><strong>agency</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p>=
<blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; paddin=
g: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>The greatness of Zemurray l=
ies in the fact that he never lost faith in his ability to salvage a situat=
ion. Bad things happened to him as bad things happen to everyone, but unlik=
e so many he was never tempted by failure. He never felt powerless or trapp=
ed. He was, as I said, an optimist. He stood in constant defiance.</em></p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>There are similar passages in the book=
s on LBJ, Vanderbilt, Ford, the Wright Brothers, the Koch Brothers, Westing=
house, Edison, and Malone. Reading about all of these people in rapid succe=
ssion &#8211; people who lived and built in a time when the world was a muc=
h harsher place than ours is today &#8211; provides a reminder that whateve=
r happens outside of you, </span><strong>you can choose to give up or you c=
an look at the board as it is and figure out how to play your next move.&#1=
60;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Maybe as importantly as the specifics, re=
ading gives you an understanding that everything that you think is novel an=
d terrifying has happened before, and that people have survived.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>So I&#8217;ll leave you with a passage from CS Lewis=
 that </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/3c1d5090-e182-43ac-b6=
33-ae55ff30bb54?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">=
Michael Dempsey tweeted this morning</a><span>:&#160;</span></p><div class=
